node.text:
Though smack dab in the middle of Los Angeles’ vibrant East Side, this home feels like a secret hideaway. Steps from a street lined with apartment buildings, modest older homes, and commercial warehouses, the single-level house, with just one window on the front facade, looks inward, becoming more open as you move through it to the surprisingly lush backyard. “We wanted to explore indoor/outdoor living in a different way,” says owner Mark Motonaga of @rioshome, who renovated the 1920s-era home with his partner, artist Guy Clouse. Read the complete feature on Atwater Hideaway, nominated in this year’s Dwell Design Awards, when you visit dwell.com/design-awards
–

node.text:
When their second child arrived, Nick and Brittany Hunt of @huntarchitecture were in need of a little extra room. The solution was right outside their Austin, Texas, residence: The backyard was big enough to build a living space and compact office where the couple could continue working from home. They kept the footprint small—under 400 square feet—and the shape simple, adding richness with a palette of burnished LaHabra stucco, wood, and steel. A tiny kitchenette/bathroom core separates the two main spaces. Overall, it was nearly $144,000 well spent, including the contractor’s fees and permits. “Leaving work at four, being able to structure your life that way, it’s a luxury,” says Nick. “And if we need to plug in for an hour or two after the kids go to bed, we just walk back here.” Brittany sums it up: “We built the work/life balance we’d always dreamed about.” See the full budget breakdown of the couple’s backyard office in our July/August issue at the link in bio, or by picking up your own copy of the magazine.
–

Paul McCobb fans, take note! The midcentury legend’s most popular designs are back thanks to @cb2. Formerly accessible only through high-end vintage markets, CB2 has revived some fan favorites from the 1950s and ’60s—spanning lighting, tables, case goods, and seating. The details that matter, such as gliding drawers and piano hinges, have been kept the same, while subtle updates to material choices nod to the present and will undoubtedly carry the pieces well into the future. To explore the collection—and see why McCobb’s designs are more relevant than ever—head to the link in bio.

Rodrigo Kong and Yoko Matsumoto-Kong had put up with their dark garden-level kitchen for more than two decades before they decided to make a change. "It was disappointing from the very beginning," recalls Rodrigo. "There were two windows for the space, but they were far away in the front of the apartment. It was small.” In more recent years, the less-than-ideal kitchen grew more bothersome, so the couple took action by hiring local firm @suzumoriarchitecture and New Jersey-based @behinhadesign. To preserve the home’s open plan, and to keep spaces flexible, the design team turned the rear parlor into a new kitchen. Open shelves crafted from black metal complement custom cabinets finished in ash. "It helped differentiate the kitchen from the existing space, making it clear that it’s a modern insertion," says Behin. "It also reinforced the sense of the kitchen being bright and airy despite its relatively small size." A central island doubles as an impromptu workspace and hangout zone, and benches by the existing bay windows now serve as "a great place for Yoko and Rodrigo to have their morning coffee before starting their day," adds Behin. For the full Before & After of the couple’s luminous new kitchen, head to the link in bio.

Three passions converge into one at this rural retreat in Australia. Ronnen Goren and Trace Streeter bought 20 acres in central Victoria with the aim of creating an enclave where farming, cooking, and hosting could all happen in the same place. “The Daylesford Longhouse is essentially a salon for food, conversations, learning, and reinventing rituals,” says Ronnen, who is also the director and founding partner of @studio.ongarato. “As a food and lifestyle destination, we aim to set a new standard for organic farming and nourishment in all senses—physical, mental, social, and cultural.” To make their vision a reality, the owners called upon the team at @partnershill, who worked with the duo to design a 328-foot-long greenhouse that incorporates all of the project’s agricultural and hospitality facilities under one roof, bringing @dlonghouse to life. Translucent panels of glass-reinforced polyester wrap around the exterior, while a specially sized roof harvests rainwater that’s collected in tanks around the site for daily use, as well as for defense against bushfires. The result is an innovative bed-and-breakfast that strikes a balance with its surroundings. Take the complete tour of the Daylesford Longhouse—and book your stay—at the link in bio.

This dreamy lakeside home in British Columbia was a long time coming. Lori Hudson and her family have owned the land, along with a tiny on-site cabin, for a decade or so. "We were just drawn to the property," she says—despite the fact that the cabin had no power, heat, or water, and that it was positioned on a steep, rocky landscape. "It wasn’t very accessible or usable," says Lori. The new, 2,500-square-foot getaway, designed by @bohlincywinskijackson, however, is pure bliss. The family (with their two Portuguese water dogs underfoot) gather around the outdoor dining table on sunny days, where black-framed doors slide out of sight to connect to the kitchen, creating an indoor/outdoor living area. But even inside, the connection to the outdoors is unavoidable through the organic material palette—birch plywood paneling brings an unfussy warmth, while large-format porcelain floor tiles are “like walking on suede,” says Lori. Then there’s the lakefront view, which never ceases to compel Lori’s paintbrush. “My kids tease me that it’s the only thing I ever paint,” she says. Take the full tour of the British Columbia home at the link in bio.

In the quaint fishing town of Olhão in Portugal’s southern region of Algarve, Portuguese architecture firm @atelierrua and Belgium-based interior design firm @studio.stories teamed up for a thoughtful reno of a former fish warehouse. Now a guesthouse available through boutique hospitality brand @the_addresses, the building’s updated design is anchored in a philosophy that stays true to the region’s heritage and overall atmosphere—“The Algarve’s good weather and traditional lifestyle were relevant to the design,” says Francisco Freitas, Atelier Rua’s principal architect. While preserving original elements and leaning heavily on the region’s material palette—like original archways, terracotta floors, and bright white walls—the interiors are more focused on the experience of “following the sun,” says Katrien de Jonghe (@katriendj), creative director of the Belgian firm. “We tried to create different corners that lend themselves to hanging out at different times of the day.” Though there is much to see around town, from horseback riding to surf lessons, guests have a pretty spectacular vista of the Rio Formosa, a 40-mile-long coastal lagoon, from the home’s rooftop that’s just one spiral staircase away. Take the complete tour of Casa Dois—and book your stay—at the link in bio.

In the seaside village of Chilmark, tucked into a quiet wooded setting, a luminous home honors its owners’ deep ties to the land. “My family has lived on Martha’s Vineyard for ten generations,” says Will Seward, a New York City–based builder by trade. When it came time to build his own home on the island, he and his partner, Michelle, knew they wanted a custom dwelling with minimalist, yet warm and approachable design that felt in harmony with its setting. Part of this harmony meant working within the natural constraints of their location, which—accessible only by boat and air—can quickly escalate costs both financial and environmental. “Building on an island is tricky,” says Jake Wright of @turkeldesign, who solved the couple’s problem with a customized take on the prefab company’s Axiom 2790 model.
Clad in ash, the multilevel residence is a sleek nod to the island’s vernacular architecture—shingle-style exteriors that become weathered and gray over time—and it provides the welcoming, human-scaled getaway the family had hoped to create. Inside, an open layout connects large gathering spaces with a double-height kitchen at the center. “It feels like one big room, which is made even bigger by windows in every direction,” says Will. To achieve the family’s desired indoor/outdoor lifestyle, Wright ensured plenty of openings throughout the home and fitted them with windows and doors from @themarvinbrand Signature Ultimate collection. “Marvin understands the kind of rigor and tolerance needed for prefab designs,” says Wright, “and their windows hold in heat in the winter and allow cooling in the summer, reducing energy use.”
“The entire prefab experience was miraculous,” says Will. “Everything came together very fast, yet ended up much less cookie-cutter than I expected.” Being back on his old stomping grounds makes Will nostalgic. He notes, “The Island has grown a lot. It’s different than it was when I was a kid, but it’s still a magical place, and I’m glad my son will get to experience it.” For the complete tour, head to the link in bio.

This very well could be the best result to come from a sibling rivalry. In a historic Victorian in London’s Kentish Town, @roar_architects reimagined a former women’s refuge as a split-level duplex for a brother-and-sister duo. Instead of duking it out over design preferences, the siblings decided to each take a flat so they could maintain control over their design preferences, and at the same time, live separately while living together. Each has their own thoughtfully designed level, but common areas like a kitchen and courtyard encourage hangouts and family time. When writer @elwinchan decided to move out of his family home in a residential section of Singapore filled with high-rises, he was seeking a stronger sense of community and street life. He landed in Tiong Bahru, an area closer to the center of the city, where he found an apartment in a building dating to 1948 with many vintage features intact. Among them were green terrazzo and mosaic floors, and Elwin liked how louvered windows, transom screens above doors and interior walls, and two balconies let ample light and cooling breezes flow through the space. Still, it needed some work. Through a friend, Elwin got in touch with @linghaoarchitects, who reimagined the apartment as a rustic but comfortable space loosely defined by porous partitions. The firm left many features untouched, and any changes made were inspired by existing spatial rhythms and raw material expression. The setting now perfectly suits Elwin’s preference for easy, casual living. “Because the apartment is so open," he says, "I get to feel like part of the neighborhood, which inspires my work and everyday life." When a Los Angeles-based entrepreneur and a writer were seeking creative refuge, they didn’t have to travel far for inspiration—the duo simply looked to their own backyard. Local landscape design firm @terremoto_landscape planted a wild and graphic garden rife with cacti and grass, and architectural designer @jeromebyron built a 245-square-foot guesthouse that serves as a work/play sanctuary for the couple and their two children. “The project was inspired by tree houses, so it naturally feels very warm and muted,” explains Byron. “However, I didn’t want everything to feel one-note, so I used the fixtures and furniture as an opportunity to introduce pops of colors to compliment the overall warmth.” Click the link in bio to take a full tour of the backyard oasis.

Ezequiel Adelmo Manasseri and María Sol Depetris had been searching for three years when they finally found their future apartment. Occupying the full second floor and an attic in one of Rosario, Argentina’s many "French-style" buildings—Haussmann-esque constructions dating from the early 20th century—the space had most recently housed an accounting firm. The walls were painted a shabby pastel yellow, but it still had many original plaster details and a "casa chorizo" layout, a succession of rooms that open to an exterior gallery. The young couple, cofounders of both the architecture studio @manasseridepetris and furniture brand Citrino (@citrino.citrino), knew they had come across something special. That was 2015. After four years of living there, it was time to make the 1,600-square-foot space a little more practical by creating private space. So they embarked on a renovation, turning the attic into an en suite bedroom, and covering the walls with a whited-out palette with bursts of color courtesy of the furniture they designed. The primary objective was to preserve the spirit of the property, so they brought in artisans, many of whom are retired, to exercise near-forgotten skills of restoring ornamental plaster features. The most striking change, pictured in the first slide, is a new stair enclosure protruding out into the apartment’s gallery that leads from a library up to the studio-turned-bedroom. It was fabricated from malleable metal-alloy panels, molded, erected, and spray painted in situ. Eze laughs, explaining that they used a car spray paint color called Gran Prix, the closest they could get to International Klein Blue while avoiding the headache of creating the formula themselves. For more on Ezequiel and María’s eye-popping stair, and the entire renovated Argentinian apartment, pick up a copy of our July/August issue, or head to the link in bio.

At this London terrace house, a new addition is connected via a glass courtyard that brings the garden inside. "I’m a keen gardener, and my partner has always wanted to build his own house, so our rebuilding project had to merge the two," says one of the owners, Graham. The enclosed garden features a completely glazed roof, and more glass on the rear elevation allows light and views to be drawn inside. An "up-and-over" window seat further enhances the connection between indoors and out. "The design revolves around the garden Graham has lovingly labored over for decades," says architect Amos Goldreich of @agarchitecture. “The extensive use of glass allowed us to seamlessly bring the garden into the home."
